00:03:54.180 --> 00:04:02.410
This scene from "Little Big Man"
came to have an allegorical meaning

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:06.610 position:56%
to me as I was researching the book.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:12.570
Custer, Dustin Hoffman actually I
kind of came to feel somewhat akin

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:16.280 position:56%
to him as I delved into the subject.

00:04:16.280 --> 00:04:22.570
And Custer for me came to personify
the mythos of the Indian Wars,

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:25.600
the many myths that
surround the Indian Wars.

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:31.720
Now, to some degree of course
myth always distorts history

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.120
but I believe that the Indian Wars

00:04:34.120 --> 00:04:38.910
of the American West are uniquely
susceptible to this phenomenon.

00:04:38.910 --> 00:04:43.470
Much of both popular
and academic history,

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:49.650
film and fiction has depicted the
period as an absolute struggle

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:56.630
between good and evil, reversing
the roles of heroes and villains

00:04:56.630 --> 00:05:01.950
as necessary to accommodate a
changing national conscience.

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:07.770
Now in the first 80 years following
the tragedy at Wounded Knee in 1891

00:05:07.770 --> 00:05:11.640
which ended the Indian Wars,
the nation had a tendency

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:16.210
to lionize the Indian
fighting army and to vilify

00:05:16.210 --> 00:05:21.100
or to trivialize the Indians
who resisted "civilization".

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:30.140
In 1970 the story reversed
itself and the pendulum swung

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:33.060
in the opposite direction,
to the opposite extreme.

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:39.130
Americans were developing an acute
sense of the countless wrongs

00:05:39.130 --> 00:05:42.750
that had been done to
the American Indian.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:49.210
Dee Brown's elegantly written and
passionately wrought "Bury My Heart

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:53.740
at Wounded Knee" and
later that same year,

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:57.590
the film "Little Big
Man" shaped a new saga

00:05:57.590 --> 00:06:01.090
that articulated the
nation's feelings of guilt.

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:05.900
In the public mind the
government and the army became seen

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:11.450
as wilful exterminators of the
native peoples of the West.

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:18.640
In "The Earth is Weeping" I have
tried to bring historical balance

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:21.810
to the story of the Indian Wars.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:26.140
The first step to presenting
a balanced history is,

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:30.420
I believe is, to strip
away the myths.

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:34.430
There are too many myths for
us to discuss them all today,

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:38.920
what I'd like to do then, is I hope
wet your appetite for the book,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:45.100
by addressing what I consider to
be the three most egregious myths

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:48.470
and most commonly-held myths
surrounding the Indian Wars.

00:06:48.470 --> 00:06:51.460
And here they are, the
first one, myth one,

00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:56.360
that the regular army was
hell-bent on killing Indians.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:07:02.750
Myth two, that government Indian
policy was exterminationist

00:07:02.750 --> 00:07:08.010
and three, that the Indians
united to resist the Whites,

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:13.860
to resist white encroachment
on their lands.

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:19.260
So, let's begin with the fallacy,
what I argue is a fallacy,

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:23.040
that the regular army was
eager to kill Indians.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:28.790
Does anyone recognize
this jaunty fellow?

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:31.810
This is George Crook and he was one

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:35.940
of the premier Indian
fighting generals in the West.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.270
He doesn't look like
much of a general,

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:40.270
he never wore a uniform out West.

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:44.320
He usually dressed in a pith
helmet and civilian clothes

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:47.670
and rode a mule, and was
less military-looking

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:49.740
than the common soldiers.

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:52.030
But he was without a
doubt one of the two

00:07:52.030 --> 00:07:55.460
or three finest generals
fighting the West.

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:57.890
And during the height of
the Indian Wars, a reporter,

00:07:57.890 --> 00:08:00.990
a newspaper reporter asked
him how he liked his job.

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:04.910
And Crook replied, not much.

00:08:04.910 --> 00:08:11.450
He said it was a hard thing to be
forced to do battle with Indians

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:15.020
who more often than
not were in the right.

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:20.760
As Crook continued, he said I do
not wonder and you will not either

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:24.930
that when Indians see their
wives and children starving

00:08:24.930 --> 00:08:29.710
and their last source of
supplies cut off, they go to war.

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:33.530
And then we are sent
out there to kill them.

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:36.000
It is an outrage.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.900
All tribes tell the same story.

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:41.590
They are surrounded on all sides.

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:45.060
The game is destroyed
or driven away.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:48.970
They are left to starve and there
remains but one thing for them

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:52.800
to do, to fight while they can.

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:58.730
Our treatment of the
Indian is an outrage.

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:04.730 position:56%
Now, that a general would offer such
a candid and forceful public defence

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:10.930
of the Indians may strike some of
you, as it did me, as implausible

00:09:10.930 --> 00:09:14.210
because it contradicts
an enduring myth,

00:09:14.210 --> 00:09:19.010
that the regular army was the
implacable foe of the Indian,

00:09:19.010 --> 00:09:21.260
and they wanted to go
out and kill Indians.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:25.640
And Crook was far from being
the only high-ranking officer

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:29.440
to protest the injustices
that were done to the Indians.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:34.850
John Pope, who was then the
commander of the huge Department

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:40.210
of the Missouri, which encompassed
nearly half the West actually

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:43.590
suggested at one point
that soldiers be sent

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:48.420
to help the Indians eliminate
white buffalo hunters.

00:09:50.510 --> 00:09:53.010
The year was 1874.

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:58.410
The buffalo hunters had decimated
the herds of Western Kansas

00:09:58.410 --> 00:10:03.590 position:56%
and early that year they began, they
set up shop in the Texas Panhandle

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:09.390
at a place called Adobe Walls and
resumed the killing of buffalo

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:11.550
on Indian reservation land,

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:15.970
buffalo that had been promised
the Indians in perpetuity.

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:24.050
When 500 warriors attacked
the despised buffalo hunters

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:29.360
at Adobe Walls in June 1874
the governor of Kansas appealed

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:34.750
to General Pope to dispatch
troops to save the white men.

00:10:34.750 --> 00:10:38.680
Pope turned the governor down flat.

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:45.380 position:56%
Indians like white men, he said, are
not reconciled to starve peacefully.

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:51.140
The buffalo hunters have justly
earned all that has befallen them.

00:10:51.140 --> 00:10:55.820
If I were to send troops to this
unlawful establishment it would be

00:10:55.820 --> 00:11:00.810
to break it up and
not to protect it.

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:03.530
Unfortunately the buffalo
hunters managed

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:06.990
to repel the Indians on their own.

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:12.050
Now, from these two episodes,
what are we to conclude?

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:17.610
And the essential truth
is that the plight

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:23.610 position:56%
of the Indians deeply disturbed most
senior officers and then more often

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:29.150
than not they sympathized with the
hostile Indians whey were charged

00:11:29.150 --> 00:11:31.150
with subduing.

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:34.240 position:56%
I could give countless more examples

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:37.490
of other generals who
felt the same way.

00:11:37.490 --> 00:11:42.340
Now, what can we say about
the government policy

00:11:42.340 --> 00:11:45.300
that they were charged
with enforcing?

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:51.750
Its wisdom or morality may be
questioned but it cannot be said

00:11:51.750 --> 00:11:58.630 position:56%
that the government ever intended to
physically exterminate, I emphasize,

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:01.770
physically exterminate the Indians.

00:12:01.770 --> 00:12:10.630
That the Indian way of life must
be eradicated, if the Indians were

00:12:10.630 --> 00:12:14.150
to survive, was however
taken for granted,

00:12:14.150 --> 00:12:18.990
even among the most ardent
advocates of Indian rights.

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:21.940
The term, the phrase
'kill the Indians,

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:25.930 position:56%
save the man' was quite common then.

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:27.460
Well, federal Indian policy

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:31.460
after the Civil War
evolved in fits and starts.

00:12:31.460 --> 00:12:34.370
When the Civil War ended,
it was in absolute tatters.

00:12:34.370 --> 00:12:36.640
Neither the president
nor Congress were able

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:41.290
to fashion a coherent
policy which left things

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:43.480 position:56%
as General William Tecumseh Sherman,

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:46.520
who was the ranking
officer the West,

00:12:46.520 --> 00:12:51.710
put it to "caprice and hazard".

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:57.620
Another great problem was
rampant corruption that ran

00:12:57.620 --> 00:12:59.700
through the Indian Bureau.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:03.550
This slide here is the
famous Thomas Nast cartoon

00:13:03.550 --> 00:13:07.830
from Harper's Weekly
showing a starving Indian

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:10.180
and a quite satisfied

00:13:10.180 --> 00:13:14.500
and heavily-laden with
cash Indian agent.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:20.470
There was a popular story told of
a chief who described his agent

00:13:20.470 --> 00:13:23.170
to General Sherman thusly.

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:26.610
He said, 'Our agent great man,

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:31.570
when he comes he brings
everything in a little bag.

00:13:31.570 --> 00:13:34.480
When he goes it takes
three steamboats

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:37.820
to carry away his things'.

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:45.050
Well, things changed in 1869

00:13:45.050 --> 00:13:47.780
with the newly-elected
President Ulysses S. Grant

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:53.220
who famously declared with respect
to the Indians 'Let us have peace'.

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:59.930
He instituted a 'carrot and stick'
policy, a carrot and stick body

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:04.230
of principles that became
known as the Peace Policy.

00:14:04.230 --> 00:14:09.530
Grant replaced the corrupt agents
with churchmen and army officers.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:13.770
He also established independent
oversight of the Indian Bureau.

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:18.900
And he directed the Indian
agents to assemble the Indians

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:24.440
in their jurisdictions on permanent
reservations that were well removed

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:29.150
from the overland travel routes
and from white settlements,

00:14:29.150 --> 00:14:32.880
get them started on the
road to "civilization"

00:14:32.880 --> 00:14:38.180
and above all treat them
with kindness and patience.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:41.040
Indians who refused to settle
on reservations would be turned

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:45.520
over to the military however and
treated as friendly or hostile

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:47.870
as circumstances might justify.

00:14:47.870 --> 00:14:54.910
Now, kindness and patience,
not to mention common decency,

00:14:54.910 --> 00:14:58.710
were often lacking in the
implementation of Grant's policy.

00:14:58.710 --> 00:15:03.880
In the ensuring years some of
the reforms that he instituted

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:08.200
like replacing these
patronage agents were abandoned

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:10.210
and the corruption resumed.

00:15:10.210 --> 00:15:15.330 position:56%
But the principles that Grant
promulgated officially guided Indian

00:15:15.330 --> 00:15:21.850
policy during the 25 years of the
Indians Wars of the American West.

00:15:21.850 --> 00:15:25.140
The end result as we
all know, however,

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:29.010
was to dispossess Indians
of their lands.

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:36.970
The question then naturally
arises, how did the Indians respond

00:15:36.970 --> 00:15:40.320
to the broken promises,
the broken treaties

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:47.710
and to the relentless white
encroachment on their lands?

00:15:47.710 --> 00:15:52.890
And that brings us to the third
enduring myth that I want to,

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:58.540
if not dispel, at least cause
you to think about this afternoon

00:15:58.540 --> 00:16:03.320
and that is the notion
that the Indians united

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:06.980
to resist white encroachment.

00:16:06.980 --> 00:16:11.840
Does anyone recognize this
kind of art, this type of art?

00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:13.280
&gt;&gt; Ledger art.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:15.050
&gt;&gt; Peter Cozzens: Ledger
art, exactly, this,

00:16:15.050 --> 00:16:21.490
Indian warriors beginning in the
mid-19th century developed a type

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:26.860
of art called Ledger art where they
would take ledger books and draw

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:29.870
or paint in them what
they considered

00:16:29.870 --> 00:16:33.350
to be their most heroic
deeds as warriors,

00:16:33.350 --> 00:16:35.890
deeds that they considered
most worthy

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:38.650
of remembering and passing on.

00:16:38.650 --> 00:16:45.560
And invariably they were
nine times out of ten,

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:48.730
pictures of them killing
Indians of other tribes.

00:16:48.730 --> 00:16:50.530
This picture you see here is

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:55.500
of a Cheyanne Indian
warrior running his lance

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.830
through a Pawnee Indian warrior.

00:16:57.830 --> 00:17:01.920
And it graphically I think
illustrates the point

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:05.570
that the Indians not
only failed to unite

00:17:05.570 --> 00:17:09.540
in opposing the westward
expansion of civilization

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:12.500
but they also continued to
make war on one another.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:17.970
And the reason for that was simply
that these were warrior cultures.

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:23.860
Inter-tribal warfare was too deeply
ingrained for them to do otherwise.

00:17:23.860 --> 00:17:32.860
A young man raised in a tribe in
the West, he owed his whole place

00:17:32.860 --> 00:17:36.630
in tribal society to his
success as a warrior.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:39.710
In some tribes a young man
could not even court a girl

00:17:39.710 --> 00:17:42.570
until had brought home war honors.

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:47.790
So, unfortunately there was no
sense of Indian-ness that we,

00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:51.140
the Indians were a common
people until it was,

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:54.030
until it was far too late.

00:17:54.030 --> 00:17:58.480
And during the course of the
Indian Wars an army officer asked a

00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:04.110
Cheyanne chief why his tribe preyed
on their Crow Indian neighbors?

00:18:05.990 --> 00:18:11.810
Well, he said, we stole the
hunting grounds of the Crows

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:13.520
because they were the best.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:15.950
We wanted more room.

00:18:15.950 --> 00:18:19.450
It was as simple as that.

00:18:19.450 --> 00:18:26.550
Or, as a Lakota chief, Lakota Sioux
chief told a government treaty

00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:32.500
negotiator, he said "You have
split my land and I do not like it.

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:37.510
These lands once belonged
to the Kiowa and to the Crow

00:18:37.510 --> 00:18:40.530
but we whipped those
nations out of them

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:43.790
and in this we did
what the white men do

00:18:43.790 --> 00:18:47.680
when they want the
lands of the Indians".

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:53.550 position:56%
Well those certainly were sentiments
that inquisitive Whites determined

00:18:53.550 --> 00:18:56.050
to clear the West of
what they considered

00:18:56.050 --> 00:18:59.900
to be troublesome Indians,
could readily appreciate.

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:06.370
Now one side point that I want to
make, that I haven't made enough

00:19:06.370 --> 00:19:11.380
in the past, is that while the
Indians fought among themselves

00:19:11.380 --> 00:19:17.710
relentlessly and throughout this
whole epic of their dispossession,

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:25.540
the Indians never provoked any
of the conflicts with the Whites

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:28.730
that you'll read about in my book.

00:19:28.730 --> 00:19:31.470
They never provoked any of them.

00:19:31.470 --> 00:19:38.680 position:56%
They were always driven to war and
I think showed remarkable restraint.

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:43.800
A kind of a subtext
of this third myth,

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:47.030
something that's frequently
lost in the mythos

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:51.190
of the Indian Wars are
the numerous tribes

00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:54.450
that actually accepted
the white presence,

00:19:54.450 --> 00:19:58.780
that actually welcomed the white
presence because it enabled them

00:19:58.780 --> 00:20:04.550
to form allies to fight
their own tribal enemies,

00:20:04.550 --> 00:20:09.400
sort of along the lines of 'the
enemy of my enemy is my friend'.

00:20:09.400 --> 00:20:12.810
The Pawnee Indians for
example were vitally important

00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:15.760
to the construction of the
Transcontinental Railroad,

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:17.930
specifically the Union-Pacific
Railroad.

00:20:17.930 --> 00:20:24.650
In the summer of 1867 the
Lakota and the Cheyanne had

00:20:24.650 --> 00:20:33.730 position:56%
so severely raided the Union-Pacific
that they essentially brought work

00:20:33.730 --> 00:20:38.930
on the road to a standstill,
to an absolute halt.

00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:45.140
The army proved incapable of
stopping these fast-moving,

00:20:45.140 --> 00:20:49.980
fast-riding Indian raiding
parties and so a battalion

00:20:49.980 --> 00:20:54.850
of Pawnees were recruited
as soldiers.

00:20:54.850 --> 00:21:00.130 position:56%
Here you see a picture of the Pawnee
battalion preparing for action.

00:21:00.130 --> 00:21:02.950
Well the Pawnee battalion, how many

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:05.960
of you have watched
"Hell on Wheels"?

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:08.610
The series, I imagine
a good number of you.

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:10.110
Well noticeably absent in "Hell

00:21:10.110 --> 00:21:13.060
on Wheels" is any mention
of the Pawnee.

00:21:13.060 --> 00:21:18.850
But they mauled one large Cheyanne
war party so badly that raids

00:21:18.850 --> 00:21:22.580
on the Union-Pacific
stopped, completely stopped

00:21:22.580 --> 00:21:25.360
and work resumed unimpeded.

00:21:25.360 --> 00:21:27.950
I think it's safe to
say that the presence

00:21:27.950 --> 00:21:31.420
of the Pawnee battalion
along the road shaved

00:21:31.420 --> 00:21:35.590 position:56%
at least a year off the construction
of the Transcontinental Railroad

00:21:35.590 --> 00:21:42.590
and probably a season or
two off of "Hell on Wheels".

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:48.200
Now, as destructive as the
fighting between tribes was,

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:51.780
what ultimately doomed the Indians,

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:57.000
doomed Indian resistance was the
inability of individual tribes

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.780
to maintain cohesion
against the white threat.

00:22:00.780 --> 00:22:05.820
Only those tribes that accepted
the Whites, tribes like the Pawnee,

00:22:05.820 --> 00:22:09.280 position:56%
the Crow, the Shoshone were unified.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:13.190
None of the tribes that are famous
to us for fighting the government

00:22:13.190 --> 00:22:18.370
like the Lakota, the Cheyanne,
the Apache, the Arapaho,

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:21.830
none of these tribes were
ever united for war or peace.

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:28.340
Each tribe had its war and peace
factions that are traditionalist

00:22:28.340 --> 00:22:33.560
and accommodation of factions
however you want to name them,

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:35.810
that struggled for dominance

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:39.560
and clashed sometimes
violently with one another.

00:22:39.560 --> 00:22:43.260
You get again the traditionalists
or war faction and the peace

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:47.260
or accommodationist
faction in each tribe.

00:22:47.260 --> 00:22:51.900
The Kiowa of the Southern Plains
offer a particularly tragic example

00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:55.510
of this, of a tribe torn asunder.

00:22:55.510 --> 00:23:00.620
The individual you see here
is named Chief Kicking Bird.

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:04.920
He was the head of the
Kiowa peace faction

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:10.450
and he singlehandedly kept nearly
all of the Kiowas out of the,

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:15.100
what was called the Red River
War which was a final struggle

00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:21.680
for the Southern Plains and that
followed on the Adobe Walls raid

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:22.980
that I mentioned earlier.

00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:27.260
So he kept almost the entire
tribe out of that war.

00:23:27.260 --> 00:23:29.870
Nonetheless when the war is
over the government decided

00:23:29.870 --> 00:23:34.370
that they would make an
example for a change of Indians

00:23:34.370 --> 00:23:39.790
who they felt were responsible
for instigating the war.

00:23:39.790 --> 00:23:46.090
And so they ordered Kicking
Bird to select a quota of Kiowa

00:23:46.090 --> 00:23:53.060
to be sent east to
Florida for imprisonment.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:57.850
You know, Kicking Bird
argued that you know,

00:23:57.850 --> 00:24:00.150
we played a very small role in it.

00:24:00.150 --> 00:24:02.430
Hardly any Kiowa were
ever in the war.

00:24:02.430 --> 00:24:03.840
Nonetheless, he was required

00:24:03.840 --> 00:24:08.670
to choose a contingent
for incarceration.

00:24:08.670 --> 00:24:13.510
So to ease the burden on the tribe
he chose mostly Mexican captives

00:24:13.510 --> 00:24:17.850
and tribal delinquents.

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:22.320
That was well and good but he
also chose a vicious war leader

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:25.240
by the name of Mamonti [phonetic]

00:24:25.240 --> 00:24:28.970
and Kicking Bird's
complicity cost him his life.

00:24:28.970 --> 00:24:34.440
As Kicking Bird saw the prisoners
off with words of affection

00:24:34.440 --> 00:24:38.990
and promise that their
incarceration would be brief,

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:43.310
which in fact it was,
Mamonti hexed him.

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:45.490
"You think you have done well.

00:24:45.490 --> 00:24:49.280
You think you are free, a
big man with the Whites,

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:54.320
but you will not live
long, I will see to that".

00:24:54.320 --> 00:25:00.820
The next day Kicking Bird
died at the age of 39

00:25:00.820 --> 00:25:03.680
after drinking a cup of coffee.

00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:07.050
The army surgeon who treated
him said he had been poisoned

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:08.940
with strychnine.

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:13.590
There had been a fatalistic element

00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:16.880
in Kicking Bird's struggle
to maintain peace.

00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:19.180
In the unending hatred
between Whites

00:25:19.180 --> 00:25:24.370
and Indians Kicking Bird
foresaw the apocalypse.

00:25:24.370 --> 00:25:32.500 position:56%
"I fear blood must flow and my heart
is sad" he told a Quaker friend

00:25:32.500 --> 00:25:35.260
before the Red River War.

00:25:35.260 --> 00:25:40.080
"The white man is strong but he
cannot kill us all in one year,

00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:45.160
it will take him two or
three, maybe four years

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:50.650
and then the world will
turn to water or burn up.

00:25:50.650 --> 00:25:57.700
It is our Mother and cannot live
when the Indians are all dead".

00:25:57.700 --> 00:26:04.130
I will close my remarks then
with Kicking Bird's words,

00:26:04.130 --> 00:26:09.310
review very quickly the three myths
that we talked about, myth one,

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:12.060
the regular army being the
implacable foe of the Indians,

00:26:12.060 --> 00:26:16.480
myth two, that government Indian
policy was exterminationist

00:26:16.480 --> 00:26:18.800
in nature and that myth three

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:22.880
that the Indians united
to resist the Whites.

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:25.630
I hope that, I know it is a lot.

00:26:25.630 --> 00:26:28.690
We could talk at great
length on this subject

00:26:28.690 --> 00:26:33.380
but I hope I've left you a
little less confused and baffled

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:38.690
than our poor friend Dustin
Hoffman here seen looking

00:26:38.690 --> 00:26:41.890
up at Custer at the Little Bighorn.

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:46.050
So with that, I will
be more than happy

00:26:46.050 --> 00:26:50.510
to answer any questions
you may have, thank you.

